node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World in Tokyo, Japan. May be an image of 1 person, playing a sport and text that says 'These Olympic High Jumpers Celebrated Sharing A Gold Medal In A Truly Joyful Moment QATAR @world'.

node.text: Gianmarco Tamberi of Italy and Mutaz Essa Barshim of Qatar both flawlessly completed a jump of 2.37 meters (7 feet, 9 1/4 inches). They then both attempted a jump of 2.39 meters, but neither could make it after three attempts each. According to the rules, they could either settle it with a jump-off or share the gold. “Can we have two golds?” Barshim asked the official. Barshim and Tamberi are rivals, but they’re also friends who have been there for each other through international competitions and even injuries. “He is one of my best friends, not only on the track, but outside the track. We work together. This is a dream come true,” Barshim said after the win, @cbc reported. Tap the link in the bio to read more 🥇🥇 (📸: Picture Alliance / DPA / Picture Alliance via Getty Images; Ian Macnicol / Getty Images)

node.text: Tokyo hosted its first modern Olympics in 1964, and it looked very different from the summer games being held today. Click our link in bio to see more archival photos 🇯🇵(📸: Al Fenn / Getty Images, Bettmann / Bettmann Archive)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World on July 27, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Uzbekistan's Oksana Chusovitina Received A Standing Ovation At Her Eighth And Final Olympic Games OFB C @world YO 20'.

node.text: The 46-year-old, two-time Olympic medalist representing Uzbekistan, finished her historic Olympic career with a vault performance, which failed to qualify her for the finals. Her emotional parting elicited many tears and cheers — from spectators, fellow competitors, and even judges. “I think I am one of the pioneers to let every woman know that you can be a wife, you can be a daughter, you can be a mother, and you can be an Olympic athlete and an Olympic medalist. Anything is possible, and age is just a number,” she told Inside Gymnastics Magazine back in May. Chusovitina has attended the games since the 1992 Summer Olympics. She was inducted into the International Gymnastics Hall of Fame in May 2017 and was named the Best Athlete of Decade (2011-2020) in Uzbekistan by the public vote held by the National Olympic Committee of Uzbekistan, according to the Olympics website 🤸(📸: Kazuhiro Nogi/AFP via Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World on July 26, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Weightlifter Hidilyn Diaz Wins First-Ever Gold Medal For The Philippines K TOKYO20 2 @world'.

node.text: Diaz, an Airwoman Sargent for the Philippine Air Force, just won gold in the women's 55kg weightlifting competition, earning the first gold medal ever for the Philippines. She set the Olympic Record for Women's 55kg by hoisting a combined weight of 224kg over her head. "I want to say to the young generation in the Philippines, 'You can have this dream of gold too,'" Diaz said to AFP. Back in the 2016 Summer Games in Rio, she won the silver medal to make her the first medalist ever for the Philippines. Tap the link in bio to read more. (📸: Chris Graythen/Getty Images)

May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'The Director Of The Olympics Opening Ceremony Has Been Fired For A Holocaust "Joke" He Made In 1998 TOKYO2020 TOKYO 2020 パラリンピックの 閉会式に出ませんか？ TOKYO2020 TOKYO PARALYMPIC GAMES TOK 2020 ステージ演出 ステー 小林賢太郎 TOKY @world'.

node.text: Kentaro Kobayashi, the director of the opening ceremony for the Tokyo Summer Olympics, was fired after footage from a 1998 comedy sketch showed him making an antisemitic Holocaust joke. The firing comes just a day before the Summer Olympics opening ceremony. “In the short time remaining before the Opening Ceremony, we offer our deepest apologies for any offense and anguish this matter may have caused to the many people involved in the Olympic Games, as well as to the citizens of Japan and the world,” the organizing committee said in a statement. Video surfaced of Kobayashi, who is known for his work as a comedian, actor, and theater director, filming a sketch parodying a children's program in which he referred to paper doll cutouts as "the ones from that time you said 'let's play the Holocaust,'" according to AFP news agency. "I understand that my foolish choice of words at the time was a mistake, and I regret it," Kobayashi said in a statement. Click our link in bio to read more. (📸: Kyodo Kyodo/Reuters)

node.text: More than 10,000 people in China's Henan province have been forced to evacuate due to record rainfall, which has caused at least 12 deaths in the city of Zhengzhou, according to the BBC. The city has seen as much rain in recent days as it would normally see in an entire year, the BBC reported. While China normally experiences flooding during the summer months, a warming atmosphere caused by climate change has made such weather events even more extreme. (📹: Reuters)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by BuzzFeed World on July 16, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'Floods In Germany Have Killed Over 100 People. These Photos Show The Devastation. কমত সয়ত @world'.

node.text: Over 100 people were killed as parts of Germany received over a month of rainfall in 24 hours, causing rivers to overflow. Rescue operations are ongoing as hundreds of people are still listed as missing. According to the Associated Press, dozens of residents were rescued from their roofs, where they had taken refuge from the rising waters. Dozens have also been killed in neighboring Belgium and the Netherlands. Weather disasters are inextricably linked to human-induced climate change. Tap the link in bio to see more. (📸: Picture Alliance / dpa/picture alliance via Getty Images; Wolfgang Rattay / Reuters; Wolfgang Rattay / Reuters; Marius Becker/ Picture Alliance via Getty Images; Christof Stache / AFP via Getty Images)

node.text: A 2-year-old girl survived unharmed after her mother threw her from a ledge to safety as they escaped a burning high-rise building in the South African city of Durban during protests, according to Reuters. The mother, Naledi Mayoni, was on the 16th floor and ran down the stairs when the fire started, according to Reuters. Mayoni also made it to safety. The building had been set on fire by looters. For almost a week now, protests turned into mass-looting have set malls ablaze and clashed with police after the jailing of ex-president Jacob Zuma, leading to the worst violence in years and resulting in dozens of people injured and killed, according to Reuters. (📸: REUTERS)

node.text: Sara, who asked that her last name be withheld to protect her family’s privacy, was sentenced in 2012 to 30 years in prison. Last month, she was freed thanks to a growing movement to defend the women facing decades in prison on similar charges. She is the latest in a slow trickle of women convicted on similar charges who are having their sentences commuted — 11 since 2017, according to the Agrupación Ciudadana por la Despenalización del Aborto, a pro–abortion rights advocacy group. The country has filed aggravated homicide charges against at least 129 women for alleged abortions since 2000. El Salvador has one of the harshest anti-abortion laws in the world, with no exceptions made even when the pregnant person’s life is in danger. Read more through the link in our bio. (📸: Erica Canepa for BuzzFeed News)

node.text: As the country faces dire shortages of basic necessities including food and medicine, and rising COVID-19 cases, thousands of Cubans took to the streets in unprecedented protest Sunday to call for an end to the decades-old communist dictatorship, the Miami Herald reported. "Patria y Vida," or "Homeland and Life," has become a slogan for activists who are protesting the country's rising inflation, declining economy, and lack of food and vaccines, according to the Herald. Rather than purchase COVID-19 vaccines from other countries, Cuba decided to make its own, but has been slow to immunize its population, with instances of COVID-19 rising to a record 6,923 cases on Sunday, the Herald reported. The surge comes as Cuba's healthcare system is on the brink of collapse, with hospitals running out of medicines as basic as penicillin and aspirin, and people waiting in long lines for basic food staples, according to the New York Times. In a statement Monday, President Biden said “We stand with the Cuban people and their clarion call for freedom,” and called Cuba’s government “an authoritarian regime." Meanwhile Cuba's president, Miguel Díaz-Canel Bermúdez, cast the protests as a dire threat to Cuba, and warned harsh action against activists: “They’ll have to walk over our dead bodies if they want to take on the revolution,” Díaz-Canel said. Díaz-Canel also attacked the ongoing US trade embargo with Cuba, which saw sanctions tightened under Trump and which Biden has yet to ease, Reuters reported. (📸: Alexandre Meneghini/Reuters)

node.text: The latest decision to bar spectators is yet another setback to the Tokyo Olympic Games, which have already been delayed by a year due to the pandemic, leading to massive costs. The state of emergency in Tokyo, which will run until Aug. 22, has been implemented to stop the flow of people into the city amid the rising number of COVID-19 cases, fueled by the spread of the highly contagious Delta variant, officials said. Tokyo reported 896 new COVID cases Thursday, with two deaths and 1,782 hospitalizations. Cases nationwide have risen approximately 17% in the last two weeks. Tap the link in bio to read more. (📸: Stanislav Kogiku/SOPA Images/LightRocket via Getty Images)

node.text: President Jovenel Moïse was assassinated and his wife, first lady Martine Moïse, critically injured when a group of gunmen attacked their home Wednesday, the Associated Press reported. Interim Prime Minister Claude Joseph called for an international investigation into the killing, and said that the country’s elections scheduled for later this year should be held as planned. Bocchit Edmond, the Haitian ambassador to the United States, said the attack on the president was “carried out by foreign mercenaries and professional killers” posing as U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agents, according to the AP. A State Department spokesperson called those claims “absolutely false,” CNN reported. Haitian authorities declared a “state of siege,” according to CNN, closing all borders and the country’s international airport, and asked the Dominican Republic to close its borders after stating that the assassins could have fled there. Moïse, who took office in 2017, had been ruling by decree for more than a year after failing to hold elections, with the opposition party and violent protests demanding his resignation. Moïse was killed just one day after nominating neurosurgeon Ariel Henry as the new prime minister, CNN reported, further adding to confusion about who will now rule the country. Haiti has long struggled to find a firm footing for democracy, most recently exacerbated by spikes in gang violence, the COVID-19 pandemic, Hurricane Matthew in 2016 and its devastating earthquake in 2010. (📸: Dieu Nalio Chery/AP)
